TY  - JOUR
T1  - Is the Resource-Based View a Practical Organizational Theory?
AU  - Arend, Richard J.
AU  - Lévesque, Moren
Y1  - 2009/12/30
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2010/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.1090.0484
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.1090.0484
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 913
EP  - 930
VL  - 21
IS  - 4
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We explore the question of whether the resource-based view (RBV) is a practical theory for managers. We test the ability of the RBV to provide two pieces of practical information: (1) the identification of the very few strategic assets from a large set of assets, and (2) the estimation of the functional form of how such strategic assets' critical VRIO characteristic levels relate to firm performance. We do so by modeling the tenets of the RBV and adjusting them in a simulation. We place ourselves in the shoes of the managers by using standard empirical methods on the simulated data to determine whether the RBV does provide practical information. We then discuss what can be done for academics and managers given that determination.
AB  - We explore the question of whether the resource-based view (RBV) is a practical theory for managers. We test the ability of the RBV to provide two pieces of practical information: (1) the identification of the very few strategic assets from a large set of assets, and (2) the estimation of the functional form of how such strategic assets' critical VRIO characteristic levels relate to firm performance. We do so by modeling the tenets of the RBV and adjusting them in a simulation. We place ourselves in the shoes of the managers by using standard empirical methods on the simulated data to determine whether the RBV does provide practical information. We then discuss what can be done for academics and managers given that determination.
